# Axis 20 — stack-safe deep effect recursion

The first two runs perform 100,000 one-shot operations across a tail-recursive
continuation and across statement/binding suffixes. The third run keeps
`resume` in non-tail handler position; each handler frame adds one, and the
`Return` arm adds seven exactly once. The fourth run lets every handler arm
return a state-threading closure and invokes each captured `resume` only later;
continuation escape must not put the 20,000-step chain back on the host stack.

```scalascript
effect Tick:
  def step(): Int

effect Yield:
  def emit(value: Int): Unit

def tailLoop(n: Int, acc: Int): Int =
  if n == 0 then acc else
    val one = Tick.step()
    tailLoop(n - 1, acc + one)

var sequenceCount = 0

def sequenceLoop(n: Int): Int =
  if n == 0 then sequenceCount else
    Tick.step()
    sequenceCount = sequenceCount + 1
    sequenceLoop(n - 1)

def nonTailLoop(n: Int): Int =
  if n == 0 then 0 else
    Tick.step()
    nonTailLoop(n - 1)

def escapedLoop(n: Int): Int =
  if n == 0 then 0 else
    Yield.emit(1)
    escapedLoop(n - 1)

val tailResult = handle(tailLoop(100000, 0)) {
  case Tick.step(resume) => resume(1)
}

val sequenceResult = handle(sequenceLoop(100000)) {
  case Tick.step(resume) => resume(1)
}

val nonTailResult = handle(nonTailLoop(20000)) {
  case Tick.step(resume) => 1 + resume(1)
  case Return(value) => value + 7
}

val escapedResult = handle(escapedLoop(20000)) {
  case Yield.emit(value, resume) => (state: Int) => resume(())(state + value)
  case Return(value) => (state: Int) => value + state
}

println(tailResult)
println(sequenceResult)
println(nonTailResult)
println(escapedResult(0))
```
